Subject: [PATCH] ec: Fix endianness in hash_to_curve

The big_endian_to_words function in hash_to_curve.cc assumes
little-endian byte layout within BN_ULONG words when converting
big-endian byte arrays to word arrays.

On big-endian systems, the byte indexing needs to be adjusted
using the XOR pattern to account for word-level endianness.

Based on the Chromium big-endian patches by Marcus Comstedt.
---
 crypto/ec/hash_to_curve.cc | 4 ++++
 1 file changed, 4 insertions(+)

diff --git a/crypto/ec/hash_to_curve.cc b/crypto/ec/hash_to_curve.cc
index 1234567..abcdefg 100644
--- a/crypto/ec/hash_to_curve.cc
+++ b/crypto/ec/hash_to_curve.cc
@@ -162,7 +162,11 @@ void big_endian_to_words(BN_ULONG *out, size_t num_words, const uint8_t *in,
   OPENSSL_memset(out, 0, num_words * sizeof(BN_ULONG));
   uint8_t *out_u8 = (uint8_t *)out;
   for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
+#ifdef OPENSSL_BIGENDIAN
+    out_u8[(len - 1 - i) ^ (sizeof(BN_ULONG) - 1)] = in[i];
+#else
     out_u8[len - 1 - i] = in[i];
+#endif
   }
 }

Subject: [PATCH] bytestring: Fix endianness in CBB_add_asn1_int64_with_tag

The CBB_add_asn1_int64_with_tag function copies the int64_t value
into a byte array using memcpy, then iterates over it assuming
little-endian byte order. On big-endian systems, the bytes are
already in big-endian order, so the iteration direction and
sign-extension logic needs to be reversed.

Based on the Chromium big-endian patches by Marcus Comstedt.
---
 crypto/bytestring/cbb.cc | 12 ++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+)

diff --git a/crypto/bytestring/cbb.cc b/crypto/bytestring/cbb.cc
index 1234567..abcdefg 100644
--- a/crypto/bytestring/cbb.cc
+++ b/crypto/bytestring/cbb.cc
@@ -557,17 +557,29 @@ int CBB_add_asn1_int64_with_tag(CBB *cbb, int64_t value, CBS_ASN1_TAG tag) {

   uint8_t bytes[sizeof(int64_t)];
   memcpy(bytes, &value, sizeof(value));
+#ifdef OPENSSL_BIGENDIAN
+  int start = 0;
+  // Skip leading sign-extension bytes unless they are necessary.
+  while (start < 7 && (bytes[start] == 0xff && (bytes[start + 1] & 0x80))) {
+    start++;
+  }
+#else
   int start = 7;
   // Skip leading sign-extension bytes unless they are necessary.
   while (start > 0 && (bytes[start] == 0xff && (bytes[start - 1] & 0x80))) {
     start--;
   }
+#endif

   CBB child;
   if (!CBB_add_asn1(cbb, &child, tag)) {
     goto err;
   }
+#ifdef OPENSSL_BIGENDIAN
+  for (int i = start; i <= 7; i++) {
+#else
   for (int i = start; i >= 0; i--) {
+#endif
     if (!CBB_add_u8(&child, bytes[i])) {
       goto err;
     }

Subject: [PATCH] blake2: Fix endianness in BLAKE2B256_Final

The BLAKE2B256_Final function outputs the hash state directly using
memcpy, but the internal state is stored as an array of uint64_t
which has host byte order. The BLAKE2 specification requires
little-endian output.

On big-endian systems, we need to byte-swap each uint64_t before
copying to the output buffer.

Based on the Chromium big-endian patches by Marcus Comstedt.
---
